Reinforcement Learning: Markov Decision Processes¶

1. Objective:¶

The purpose of this project is to explore the 3 different reinforcement learning algorithms and analyze their performance on two different discrete Markov Decision Processes. Value iteration, Policy Iteration and Q Learning algorithms are implemented for two MDPs, one with small number of states while other with large number of states. These MDPs also differ in terms of reward function and transition models. Results of these algorithms are then analyzed and compared on various performance metrics. These performance metrics include similarities in the policies generate, convergence rate and runtimes.

2. Markov Decision Process¶

Markov Decision Process (MDP) provides the mathematical framework to model the decision-making process for deterministic as well as stochastic problems. MDPs are particularly useful to solve real world problems where outcome of actions performed by an agent is partially random and partially controlled by the agent. These decision making problems can ne solved using MDPs only if the Markov property is followed which states that the future of the system state depends only on the current state and not on the any sequence of past states.

A Markov Decision Process is a tuple <S,A,P,R,>

  • S = finite set of states
  • A = finite set of actions
  • P = state transition probability matrix: Pss' = P[St+1=s' | St=s, At=a]
  • R = reward function: Rs = E[Rt+1 | St = s, At=a]
  • = discount factor

To solve the MDPs we identify the optimal Policy which defines the behavior of an agent and it is a distribution over actions given states:

(a|s) = P[At=a | St=s]

It is also assumed that MDPs are stationary which means policy function only depend on the given state and it is not affected by any other factor. To avoid infinite runs of cyclic Markov process and to represent uncertainty about the future rewards are discounted.

The state-value function v(s) tells us how good it is to be in a given state. It gives us expected return starting from the state s, and then following policy .

v(s) = E[Gt | St=s]

The action-value function q(s,a) tells us what action to take given the agent is in particular state. It gives the expected return starting from state s, taking action a, and then following policy .

q(s,a) = E[Gt | St=s, At=a]

Using Bellman Equation state-value function and action-value function can again be further decomposed into immediate reward plus discounted value of successor state

v(s) = E[Rt+1 + v(St+1) | St=s]

q(s,a) = E[Rt+1 + q(St+1,At+1) | St=s, At=a]

3. Algorithms Implemented & Evaluation Criterion¶

3.1 Value Iteration¶

This algorithm is also known as backward induction and it uses Bellman Equations to repeatedly update the estimated value function until optimal value function v(s) is found. The algorithm randomly initializes v(s) and iteratively updates the q(s, a) and v(s) values until they converges. Value iteration is guaranteed to converge to the optimal values. Below is the Value Iteration algorithm [1]

3.2 Policy Iteration¶

Value iteration repeatedly iterates until it converges to optimal value function but our goal is to find the optimal policy which could have converged before convergence of optimal value. Policy iteration computes policy value at each step and stops when the policy value is converged. Policy iteration algorithm performs faster as compared to value iteration algorithm because policy converges more quickly than a value function. Below is the Policy Iteration algorithm [1]

3.3 Q Learning¶

Q learning is model free algorithm. Unlike the Value and Policy iteration models, Q Learning drive the optimal policy without explicitly learning transitions and value gained. Q Learning do not depend on the knowledge of the underlying uncertainties in transition and associated rewards. Q Learning algorithm allows agent to explore the environment by implementing random actions to explore the environment. Below is the Q Learning algorithm [2]

3.4 Packages Used¶

MDP toolbox provides classes and functions for the resolution of discrete-time Markov Decision Processes. To implement three reinforcement learning algorithms, fork of MDPToolBox is used. Frozen lake environment provided by OpenAI Gym is used for Grid World problem whereas example Forest Manage problem available in the MDP Toolbox is used as second MDP problem. Other standard packages such as pandas, numpy, matplotlib and seaborn are used in this project.

MDP Toolbox: https://github.com/hiive/hiivemdptoolbox
OpenAi Gym: https://github.com/openai/gym/wiki/FrozenLake-v0

3.5 Implementation Steps & Evaluation Criterion¶

Project implements three reinforcement learning algorithms on first on the Grid World MDP problem (Frozen Lake) and then on the non-grid world problem (Random Forest). For each of the problem, Value Iteration and Policy Iteration algorithms are tuned to find optimal discount factor (gamma) and stopping criterion (epsilon). Q Learning algorithm is then tuned for discount factor, number of iterations and decay rate. Performance of Q Learning algorithm is then compared with value iteration and policy iteration algorithms. The performance of these algorithms are compared using metrics such as runtime, success rate, max value and iterations. Their optimal policy is also compared to evaluate performance.

4. Problems Solved¶

4.1. Frozen Lake (Grid World Problem)¶

Frozen lake is a grid world environment which is rectangular in shape and it is divided into square tiles on which agent can walk. Just like a frozen lake like most of the tiles represent thick ice and they are walkable. But for some of the tiles represent thin ice and if agent walks on these tiles it will fall into a lake. For this implementation, environment is set to have 85% of the tiles walkable and 15% of the tiles has holes. This environment has starting point represented by S which is safe title. Tiles represented as F are frozen surface and they are safe. Tiles marked as F are holes and agent falls through these holes which ends the episode. Tiles with G represents the Goal tile and agent is rewarded 1 if goal tile is reached and episode ends. There is no reward on any other tile. In the selected environment first tile (0,0) in the top left corner is a starting point and bottom right (n,n) is the Goal tile in the nxn grid problem.

Agent can take four actions, move left (0), down (1), right (2) or up (3). Like the real world frozen lake has slippery surface, this environment is also stochastic. That means if agent tries to move up, there is only 33% chance that it will actually move up whereas 33% chance for each left or right movement.

Why this is an interesting problem? Although grid world problems look abstract but closely resemble some real-world problems like robotic automation for order fulfillment process in the warehouse or a distribution centers. For example, robots at warehouse must navigate through aisles avoiding fixed structures such as pillar etc. in their path. The ultimate goal is to specific location to retrieve an item. Stochastic nature of grid world problem also represents real world scenarios where floor is slippery or motor that drives the robot is not accurately calibrated. It will be interesting to see how algorithms behave for different values hyper parameters such discounted rate, stopping criteria etc. As warehouse can be very large. it will also be interesting to see how size of the problem affects the performance of the algorithms.

Create frozen lake environment

In [2]:
flsz = 6
flrmap = generate_random_map(size=flsz, p=0.85)
flenv = gym.make("FrozenLake-v0", desc=flrmap, is_slippery = True)
flenv.reset()
flenv.render()

flstates = flenv.observation_space.n
flactions = flenv.action_space.n

fltrans = np.zeros((flactions, flstates, flstates))
flrewards = np.zeros((flstates, flactions))

for state in flenv.env.P:
    for action in flenv.env.P[state]:
        for opt in flenv.env.P[state][action]:
            fltrans[action][state][opt[1]] += opt[0]
            flrewards[state][action] += opt[2]

4.2. Forest Management (Non-Grid World Problem)¶

Forest management has two objectives, first is to maintain the old forest for wildlife conservation and second objective is to generate profit by cutting the wood. With these two objectives in mind, each year decision is taken to perform one of two actions: Wait or Cut. Each year there is a probability p that burns down the forest. State space S represents the number of classes of the trees. Once the trees reach to the oldest states there is a rewards r1 and r2 associated actions Wait and Cut respectively. For this project wildlife conservation has higher reward of 4 as compared to cutting the forest which has reward of 2. Probability of wildfire is 10% each year. Tress are divided into 500 classes where each class represent the age of trees.

Why this is an interesting problem? Forest management is a real world challenge in current environment where one hand wildlife and their habitats are lost to indiscriminate forest cutting and on the other hand wildfires are burning down the large areas of forest which leads to loss of wood which could have cut down for its value. Uncertainty of wildfire represented as p in this problem and large set of states makes this problem very interesting. For such large number of states, it will be interesting to see if Q Learning performs better than Value Iteration and Policy Iteration.

Create environment for forest management problem

fmsz = 500

5. Value Iteration and Policy Iteration¶

5.1 Optimal value of Discount Factor (Gamma)¶

In this part Value Iteration and Policy Iteration algorithms are implemented for gamma values in the range of 0.01 and 0.99 for both Frozen Lake and Forest management algorithms. It was observed that different values of gamma results in different optimal policies. policies. Both algorithms put more emphasis on the short-term gains when value of gamma is lower whereas emphasis is more on long term gains when gamma is closer to 1.

5.1.1 Frozen Lake - Optimal value of Discount Factor (Gamma)¶

Notice that as value of gamma is closer to, number of iterations and run tine for Value Iteration increases exponentially. When gamma is closer to 1, policy iteration converges in much lesser iterations and faster than value iteration. Policy iteration required fewer iterations because it performed the maximization over the action set at each iteration of the outer loop. Both Value Iteration and Policy Iteration generated exact same rewards over the range of gamma values.

In [4]:
vistats = []
pistats = []
fig, axs = plt.subplots(nrows=1, ncols=3, figsize=(10,4));

gammas = np.arange(0.1, 0.99, 0.04)

for gamma in gammas:
    vi = ValueIteration(fltrans, flrewards, gamma)
    vi.run()
    time = vi.time
    maxV = np.amax(vi.V)    
    iters = vi.iter
    vistats.append(['VI', flsz, gamma, time, maxV, iters])

    pi = PolicyIterationModified(fltrans, flrewards, gamma)
    pi.run()
    time = pi.time
    maxV = np.amax(pi.V)    
    iters = pi.iter
    pistats.append(['PI', flsz, gamma, time, maxV, iters])

dfvi = pd.DataFrame(vistats, columns=['Type', 'Size', 'Gamma',  'Time', 'MaxV',  'Iterations'])
dfpi = pd.DataFrame(pistats, columns=['Type', 'Size', 'Gamma',  'Time', 'MaxV',  'Iterations'])

axs[0].set_title('Iterations vs Gamma')

5.2 Optimal value of stopping criterion (Epsilon)¶

In this step the both Value Iteration and Policy Iteration algorithms were implemented for range of stopping criterion starting from 0.001 till 0.05. Value if this epsilon defines the stopping criteria for both of these algorithms. At each iteration Value function calculates the delta and if this delta is lesser than value of epsilon, algorithm stops. If value of epsilon is too low, then algorithms will take too long to converge on the other hand if value of epsilon is too high then algorithms will converge too quickly without optimal policy.

5.2.1 Frozen Lake - Optimal value of stopping criterion (Epsilon)¶

From the graphs of the frozen lake problem it can see that number of iteration and runtime increase as value of epsilon closes to 0. Also, the Max Value decreases with increase in the value of epsilon. Although value iteration is simple it is computationally heavy hence higher runtime. Notice that Value iteration takes more time as well as iterations but overall performance in terms of Max Value is similar.

5.3 Optimal Policy¶

Optimal policy maximizes expected sum of rewards and in this section, optimal policy generated by Value Iteration and Policy Iteration is compared. Ideally it is expected that the policy generated on the problem with smaller state space matches for both of these algorithms because of the low complexity of the problems.

5.3.1 Frozen Lake - Optimal Policy¶

As expected, optimal policy generated by both Value Iteration and Policy Iteration algorithm matches for the Frozen Lake problem. This problem has very small state space and small number of actions both algorithms converged and generated the same optimal policy.

5.4 Varying problem size¶

In this section, results of the algorithms are analyzed for the different problem sizes to understand the performance of the algorithms.

5.4.1 Frozen Lake - Different problem sizes¶

For Frozen Lake problem, grid size range of 4x4 to 50x50 was used and performance metrics of both Value Iteration and Policy Iteration algorithms were measured and compared. As it can be seen from the below graphs, Max Value generated by both of these algorithms matched exactly for each grid size. One reason for this result could be that even at grid size of 50x50 problem was not complex and actions were limited to 4. Runtime for Policy Iteration was slightly higher than that of Value iteration which is in line with the previous results. As expected, value iteration algorithm took more iterations to converge but the interesting point to note is the difference in number of iterations required to converged increased with increase in size. This can be attribute to slight increase in complexity as problem size increases.

In [10]:
vistats = []
pistats = []

gridsizes = range(4, 50, 1)
gamma = 0.99
for sz in gridsizes:
    rmap = generate_random_map(size=sz, p=0.85)
    env = gym.make("FrozenLake-v0", desc=rmap, is_slippery = True)
    env.reset()

    states = env.observation_space.n
    actions = env.action_space.n

    trans = np.zeros((actions, states, states))
    rewards = np.zeros((states, actions))

    for state in env.env.P:
        for action in env.env.P[state]:
            for opt in env.env.P[state][action]:
                trans[action][state][opt[1]] += opt[0]
                rewards[state][action] += opt[2]

                
    vi = ValueIteration(trans, rewards, gamma)
    vi.run()
    time = vi.time
    maxV = np.amax(vi.V)    
    iters = vi.iter
    vistats.append(['VI', sz, gamma, time, maxV, iters])        

    pi = PolicyIterationModified(trans, rewards, gamma)
    pi.run()
    time = pi.time
    maxV = np.amax(pi.V)    
    iters = pi.iter
    pistats.append(['PI', sz, gamma, time, maxV, iters])

#     time = ql.time
#     maxV = np.amax(ql.V)    
#     iters = 0
#     qlstats.append(['QL', sz, gamma,  time, maxV, iters])

5.4.2 Forest Management - Analyze results of varying size¶

For forest management problem size was varied from 5 to 500 and noticeable difference was observed in the Max Value and number of iterations required to converge even for the smaller size of the problem. The runtime for both of the algorithms was very close until problem size was 350 after that runtime of policy iteration exponentially increase till size 500.

6. Q Learning¶

6.1 Optimal value of Discount Factor (Gamma)¶

As discussed in the section 6.1, lower value of gamma give more preference to short term gains whereas higher value of gamma give preference to long term gains.

6.3 Exploration vs Exploitation & Optimal Policy¶

In this section, Q Learning algorithm is tuning to maximize the reward by exploration vs exploitation trade-off. Epsilon greedy strategy is implemented which uses higher epsilon rate at the beginning as agent explores the environment and chooses the actions at random. Epsilon rate is decayed as agent explores more and more environment over the period of time and agent starts exploiting the explored environment. Below Q table was generated for the Frozen Lake problem and score of 0.75 was achieved. Performance of the Q Learning algorithm was closely to Value Iteration and Policy Iteration algorithms on the Frozen Lake problem. But on the Forest management problem Q Learning did not perform optimally and more hyper parameter tuning was required which I was unable to perform due to the size of the problem.

Code in this section was adapted from https://python-data-science.readthedocs.io/en/latest/reinforcement.html

In [28]:
action_size = flenv.action_space.n
state_size = flenv.observation_space.n
qtable = np.zeros((state_size, action_size))

# define hyperparameters ----------
total_episodes = 15000        # Total episodes
learning_rate = 0.7           # Learning rate
max_steps = 100000             # Max steps per episode
gamma = 0.9                  # Discounting rate

# Exploration parameters
epsilon = 0.1                 # Exploration rate
max_epsilon = 1.0             # Exploration probability at start
min_epsilon = 0.00001            # Minimum exploration probability
decay_rate = 0.005             # Exponential decay rate for exploration prob

# List of rewards
rewards = []

# 2 For life or until learning is stopped
for episode in range(total_episodes):
    # Reset the environment
    state = flenv.reset()
    step = 0
    done = False
    total_rewards = 0

    for step in range(max_steps):
        # 3. Choose an action a in the current world state (s)
        ## First we randomize a number
        exp_exp_tradeoff = random.uniform(0, 1)

        ## If this number > greater than epsilon --> exploitation (taking the biggest Q value for this state)
        if exp_exp_tradeoff > epsilon:
            action = np.argmax(qtable[state,:])

        # Else doing a random choice --> exploration
        else:
            action = flenv.action_space.sample()

        # Take the action (a) and observe the outcome state(s') and reward (r)
        new_state, reward, done, info = flenv.step(action)

        # Update Q(s,a):= Q(s,a) + lr [R(s,a) + gamma * max Q(s',a') - Q(s,a)]
        # qtable[new_state,:] : all the actions we can take from new state
        qtable[state, action] = qtable[state, action] + learning_rate * (reward + gamma * np.max(qtable[new_state, :]) - qtable[state, action])

        total_rewards += reward

        # Our new state is state
        state = new_state

        # If done (if we're dead) : finish episode
        if done == True:
            break

    # Reduce epsilon (because we need less and less exploration)
    epsilon = min_epsilon + (max_epsilon - min_epsilon)*np.exp(-decay_rate*episode)
    rewards.append(total_rewards)

print ("Score over time: " +  str(sum(rewards)/total_episodes))
print(qtable)
